<font color="#FF0000">UNDERSTANDING</font><br>
<tt>Sat Jun 14 22:24:50 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
This is a very important set of perspectives for me to understand.<br><br>
I recently remarked to a friend that I sometimes felt more at ease with Vietnamese than I have at some times with my own people. I am not speaking of idiology here, but a sense of understanding and respect that I feel when I interact with Vietnamese. There is a connection that seems to transcend the affairs of the moment.<br><br>
I do not feel that forgiveness is the issue. I feel rather that understanding is more the quality that I appreciate and personally seek. I now view much of what I have written on this site over many months as partially a way to have others understand where I have been, where I was headed, and how I really felt about it all. In the Vietnamese (and in other Vietnam Veterans) I sense a better appreciation for those things than perhaps I see or sense from others.<br><br>
As I see it, seeking and receiving understanding for all of us is what is really important. I never expect to be &quot;forgiven&quot;.   
